<webwork-reps version="2" webwork2_major_version="2" webwork2_minor_version="20" xml:id="extracted-section-fractions-and-fraction-arithmetic-9-1-10-9" assembly-id="section-fractions-and-fraction-arithmetic-9-1-10-9">
  <static seed="63" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions20.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{1}{10} + \frac{1}{9}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{19}{90}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>10</m> and <m>9</m> is <m>90</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{1}{10}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>90</m>, we multiply <m>9</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{1}{10} \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 9}{10 \cdot 9}\\ \amp = \frac{9}{90}\end{aligned} }</m></p>
<p>Similarly, we change the second fraction<rsq/>s denominator to <m>90</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{1}{9} \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 10}{9 \cdot 10}\\ \amp = \frac{10}{90} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Now we can add those two fractions. The full process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{1}{10} + \frac{1}{9}
        \amp = \frac{9}{90} + \frac{10}{90} \\
        \amp = \frac{9 + 10}{90} \\
        \amp = \frac{19}{90}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{19}{90}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
